**MULTI-TIMER DISTINCT CHIMES** (different frequencies per timer — kitchen-timer style 'distinct chime per timer'):
```javascript
// Use the timer index modulo notes-array length to assign each timer a different note.
const CHIME_NOTES = [523.25, 587.33, 659.25, 698.46, 783.99, 880.00, 987.77]; // C5..B5
function playTimerChime(timerIndex) {
  const freq = CHIME_NOTES[timerIndex % CHIME_NOTES.length];
  const ctx = getAudioCtx();
  // Sustained 0.8s chime with envelope
  const osc = ctx.createOscillator();
  const gain = ctx.createGain();
  osc.type = 'sine';
  osc.frequency.setValueAtTime(freq, ctx.currentTime);
  gain.gain.setValueAtTime(0, ctx.currentTime);
  gain.gain.linearRampToValueAtTime(0.5, ctx.currentTime + 0.02);
  gain.gain.exponentialRampToValueAtTime(0.001, ctx.currentTime + 0.8);
  osc.connect(gain).connect(ctx.destination);
  osc.start(ctx.currentTime);
  osc.stop(ctx.currentTime + 0.8);
}
```

**IMPORTANT RULES:**
- ALWAYS define `getAudioCtx()` once and reuse — creating a new AudioContext per sound leaks resources.
- Trigger first sound from a user gesture (click/tap) — browsers block autoplay otherwise. The user clicking 'Start Timer' or 'Test Sound' counts as a gesture, so subsequent timer-end chimes work.
- DO NOT use `<audio src="data:audio/mpeg;base64,...">` — that's where models hallucinate massive blobs of fake base64 that won't decode. Web Audio API is the correct path.
- DO NOT use `new Audio('foo.mp3')` referring to external files — they won't exist in the rendered miniApp sandbox.
